images.description:
I have no idea what went on before or after to prompt this ‘quick’ getaway…crack maybe. 
*NOTE*
(A added disclosure, the words “crack” and “getaway” have no association with race, and leaving baiting comments like that shows that society today still has a lot to do when it comes to racism and discrimination)

The picture here is a picture of a cattle car. The Nazis used cattle cars to transport the prisoners like a live stock to different camps. “They would pack so many of us in that I was crushed between three other men and the wall. But it was like that for everyone. I couldn’t even raise my arm. I felt trapped again” (Gratz, 66). On the cattle car, there was a small ventilation grate. That small ventilation windows job was to ventilate the cattle car filled with over 200 men. The prisoners stood squeezed in the train car for half a day while the Nazis loaded more prisoners into other cars. The prisoners had no food or water, and no way to go to the bathroom. The destination of the cattle cars was on the side of the car. When stopped and parked across from other Jews in cattle cars, Jews would tell each other where their cars were heading by reading the side of the car.

Dagmar bumpers (also known as "bullet bumpers") is slang for the chrome conical-shaped bumper guards.  The term evokes the prominent bosom of Dagmar, a buxom early-1950s TV personality featuring low-cut gowns and conical bra cups.
